  "prompt": "What are the main reasons why students from Boston University don't graduate on time?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why students from Boston University (BU), or any university, might not graduate on time. These reasons often vary depending on individual circumstances but can generally be grouped into the following categories:\n\n### 1. **Academic Challenges**\n   - **Difficulty with Coursework:** Struggling with the academic rigor of certain courses or majors can lead to retaking classes or switching majors, delaying graduation.\n   - **Low GPA or Academic Probation:** Students who fall below the required GPA may need to retake courses or take fewer classes to improve their performance.\n   - **Failure to Meet Degree Requirements:** Misunderstanding or overlooking specific graduation requirements (e.g., core courses, major requirements, or credits) can extend time to graduation.\n\n### 2. **Financial Constraints**\n   - **Tuition Costs:** Financial difficulties may force students to reduce their course load or take time off to work, slowing their progress.\n   - **Scholarship or Aid Loss:** Losing financial aid or scholarships due to academic performance or other reasons can disrupt enrollment.\n\n### 3. **Personal or Health Issues**\n   - **Health Problems:** Physical or mental health challenges can lead to leaves of absence or reduced course loads.\n   - **Family Responsibilities:** Some students may need to prioritize family obligations, such as caregiving or financial support, over their studies.\n\n### 4. **Transferring or Switching Majors**\n   - **Changing Majors:** Students who switch majors late in their academic journey may need to complete additional coursework, delaying graduation.\n   - **Transfer Credits:** Transfer students may face challenges with credit transfers not counting toward their degree requirements, extending their time at BU.\n\n### 5. **Limited Course Availability**\n   - **Overenrollment or Class Bottlenecks:** High-demand courses with limited seats can make it difficult for students to enroll in required classes on schedule.\n   - **Course Scheduling Conflicts:** Conflicting course schedules may prevent students from taking all the classes they need in a given semester.\n\n### 6. **Extracurricular Commitments**\n   - **Study Abroad or Internships:** While valuable, these experiences can sometimes extend graduation timelines if they interfere with completing degree requirements.\n\n### 7. **Administrative or Institutional Factors**\n   - **Advising Miscommunication:** Inadequate academic advising can lead to confusion about graduation requirements or course planning.\n   - **Policy Changes:** Changes in university policies or degree requirements can affect students\u2019 academic progress.\n\n### 8. **Pandemic-Related Disruptions**\n   - **COVID-19 Impact:** The pandemic caused disruptions in education, including remote learning challenges, mental health struggles, and altered academic plans, which may have delayed graduation for some students.\n\n### Addressing the Issue\nTo mitigate these challenges, BU offers resources such as academic advising, tutoring, mental health support, and financial aid counseling. Students are encouraged to proactively engage with these resources to stay on track for timely graduation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
